---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LayerSection from '../components/LayerSection.astro';
import { compilerLayers } from '../data/compilerLayers.js';
import Tokenizer from '../components/Tokenizer.svelte';
import BytecodeVm from '../components/BytecodeVm.svelte';
import Optimize from '../components/Optimize.svelte';
import AstTree from '../components/AstTree.svelte';
import Runtimes from '../components/Runtimes.svelte';
import Registers from '../components/Registers.svelte';
import TypeCheck from '../components/TypeCheck.svelte';
import Scopes from '../components/Scopes.svelte';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import SeeAlso from '../components/SeeAlso.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
import Advanced from '../components/Advanced.astro';
import Quiz from '../components/Quiz.svelte';
import PrevNext from '../components/PrevNext.astro';
const L = Object.fromEntries(compilerLayers.map((l) => [l.id, l]));
const title = 'THE STACK — the compiler';
const description = 'A deep dive into how code stops being text: lexing into tokens, parsing into an AST, lowering to bytecode, optimizing, allocating registers, and running it — interpreted, compiled, or JIT.';
---
<Base {title} {description} layers={compilerLayers}>
  <div slot="hero">
    <div class="kicker">A deep dive into layer 08</div>
    <h1 class="title">THE <em>COMPILER</em><br />STACK</h1>
    <p class="lede">You write <code>3 + 4 * 2</code>; the CPU runs numbered operations. Between them is a pipeline that scans, parses, lowers, optimizes, and finally executes — turning text into something a machine can obey.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta"><a class="back-link" href="/">← back to the full stack</a> · source → tokens → tree → type check → bytecode → optimize → registers → run</div>
  </div>

  <LayerSection {...L.K0}>
    <p class="prose">Source code is a <b>human</b> artifact: names, indentation, comments, infix math like <code>3 + 4 * 2</code>. The machine cares about none of it — to run, the text has to be taken apart and rebuilt as operations.</p>
    <Takeaway>Source is for people; everything below this layer exists to translate it into something a CPU can execute.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Real pipelines aren't one straight shot from text to machine code — they pass through one or more <b>intermediate representations (IRs)</b>. A typical compiler lowers source to a high-level IR, then a mid-level one (LLVM's <code>IR</code>, GCC's <code>GIMPLE</code>), then a low-level, target-shaped one before emitting assembly.</p>
      <p>The payoff is the classic <b>front-end / back-end split</b>: <i>N</i> languages and <i>M</i> targets would naively need <i>N×M</i> compilers, but a shared IR turns that into <i>N</i> front ends plus <i>M</i> back ends. It's why <code>clang</code>, <code>rustc</code>, and <code>swiftc</code> can all reuse LLVM's optimizer and code generators.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A CPU executes numbered instructions, but people write expressive text full of conventions a processor has no concept of."
      idea="Treat the source as input to a pipeline of transformations, each step a little closer to machine operations."
      tradeoff="More translation stages mean more to build and more places for bugs, but also room to check errors early and optimize."
      next="The first transformation is the simplest: chop the text into tokens."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K1}>
    <p class="prose">The <b>scanner</b> (lexer) reads the characters left to right and groups them into <span class="hl">tokens</span> — a number, an operator — throwing away whitespace. It's the same idea as reading letters into words.</p>
    <Tokenizer client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Lexing turns a flat character stream into a clean stream of typed tokens the parser can reason about.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Most token classes are <b>regular languages</b>, so a lexer is really a <b>deterministic finite automaton</b>: tools like <code>lex</code>/<code>flex</code> compile your regexes into one big DFA that reads each character once and changes state — which is why scanning is linear in the input size.</p>
      <p>The hard parts are the edges. <b>Maximal munch</b> (always take the longest valid token) decides that <code>&gt;&gt;=</code> is one token, not three. Some languages also need <b>lexer/parser feedback</b> — C's famous "is <code>(T)</code> a cast or a call?" ambiguity needs the symbol table — and indentation-sensitive languages like Python have the lexer emit synthetic <code>INDENT</code>/<code>DEDENT</code> tokens.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Working character by character is painful: the parser would constantly re-ask “is this a digit? a space? part of a number?”"
      idea="Do that classification once up front, producing tokens with a type and text, so later stages work with words instead of letters."
      tradeoff="The lexer must agree exactly with the language's rules (what's a valid number, identifier, operator) or everything downstream misreads the program."
      next="A flat list of tokens still has no structure — parsing gives it a shape."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K2}>
    <p class="prose">The <b>parser</b> turns the token stream into a tree (an <span class="hl">AST</span>) that captures structure and <b>precedence</b>: because <code>×</code> binds tighter than <code>+</code>, the multiply sits deeper, so it's <span class="hl">evaluated first</span>. Step the parse to reduce it bottom-up — then flip to a naive left-to-right parse and watch the same tokens give a different answer.</p>
    <AstTree client:visible />
    <Takeaway>The AST is the program's meaning made explicit — grammar and precedence baked into the shape of a tree.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Hand-written parsers are usually <b>recursive descent</b>: one function per grammar rule, calling each other to mirror the nesting. It's clear, but encoding a dozen precedence levels as a separate function each (<code>parseAdditive</code> calls <code>parseMultiplicative</code> calls …) is tedious, and naive left recursion like <code>expr → expr + term</code> loops forever.</p>
      <p><b>Pratt parsing</b> (precedence climbing) fixes both: it attaches a binding power to each operator token and parses expressions with a single loop, only recursing while the next operator binds tighter than the current level. One compact routine handles every precedence and associativity — which is why it's the go-to for expression grammars in tools like <code>clang</code> and many language servers.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Tokens in a row are ambiguous: does 3 + 4 * 2 mean (3 + 4) * 2 or 3 + (4 * 2)? Order changes the answer."
      idea="Parse the tokens against the language's grammar into a tree where nesting encodes precedence and associativity — no ambiguity left."
      tradeoff="Grammars get intricate fast, and good error messages (“expected a ) here”) are surprisingly hard to produce from a parser."
      next="A well-formed tree can still be nonsense — type checking decides if it means anything."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K3}>
    <p class="prose">A tree can parse perfectly and still be meaningless — like multiplying a string by a number. <b>Type checking</b> (semantic analysis) walks the AST <span class="hl">bottom-up</span>, infers a type for each node, and verifies every operator's operands. Catch the error here and it never reaches the user. Toggle in a bug below.</p>
    <TypeCheck client:visible />
    <p class="prose">Before it can check types, semantic analysis has to <b>resolve names</b>: when you write <code>x</code>, <i>which</i> declaration is that? The resolver keeps a <span class="hl">symbol table</span> per scope and walks <b>outward</b> through enclosing scopes until one matches — so an inner name <span class="hl">shadows</span> an outer one, and a name found nowhere is an error. Step through a few references below.</p>
    <Scopes client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Type checking is the compiler reading for <i>meaning</i>, not just grammar — resolving every name to its declaration and rejecting programs that would misbehave, before a single instruction is generated.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Many functional languages don't make you annotate types — they <b>infer</b> them. <b>Hindley–Milner</b> inference assigns each subexpression a type variable, generates equations from how values are used, and <b>unifies</b> them: solving for a consistent assignment, or reporting a conflict. It even generalizes unconstrained variables into <b>polymorphism</b>, so <code>id x = x</code> is inferred as <code>∀a. a → a</code> with no annotation written.</p>
      <p>Name resolution underneath has its own subtlety: a single flat symbol table isn't enough, because the same name can mean different things in different <b>namespaces</b> (types vs values vs labels) and scopes. Compilers typically build a chain of scopes and, for forward references like mutually recursive functions, resolve in <b>two passes</b> — collect declarations first, then check bodies.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A grammatically valid program can still be nonsense — adding a number to a function, calling an undefined name — and running it would crash or corrupt data."
      idea="Walk the AST inferring and checking types (and scopes), so whole classes of bugs are caught at compile time instead of at runtime."
      tradeoff="It constrains what you can express and adds a phase to compile, and a type system strong enough to be useful is hard to design and sometimes fights the programmer."
      next="Once the tree is known to be meaningful, it’s safe to lower into linear operations."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K4}>
    <p class="prose">Walking the tree, the compiler emits a flat list of <b>bytecode</b> for a simple stack machine: push the operands, then let each operator pop two and push the result. Evaluating it is exactly the fetch-decode-execute loop of layer 06.</p>
    <BytecodeVm client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Lowering turns the tree into a linear instruction stream — the bridge from "structure" to "operations a machine runs."</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="cpu" note="the fetch-decode-execute loop that actually runs this bytecode" />
    <Advanced>
      <p>The widget shows a <b>stack machine</b> (operands pushed and popped, like the JVM or CPython), which is compact and trivial to generate. <b>Register VMs</b> (Lua 5, Android's Dalvik) instead name virtual registers, so <code>a = b + c</code> is one instruction instead of push-push-add-store — fewer dispatches per program, at the cost of bigger instructions and a register allocator.</p>
      <p>When lowering targets real hardware rather than a VM, the generated code must obey the platform's <b>ABI / calling convention</b>: which registers carry the first arguments, who saves which registers across a call (<b>caller-saved</b> vs <b>callee-saved</b>), how the stack is aligned, and where the return value lands. Following it exactly is what lets code from different compilers — and the OS — link and call into each other.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A tree is convenient to reason about but not to execute; hardware and VMs run a linear sequence of simple operations."
      idea="Traverse the AST and emit stack-machine (or register) instructions, so evaluation becomes a tight loop over a flat program."
      tradeoff="Different targets (a VM's bytecode vs a real ISA) want different lowerings, and naive code generation leaves obvious waste behind."
      next="That waste is what the optimizer removes."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K5}>
    <p class="prose">Before running, the compiler rewrites the program to do <b>less work for the same result</b>. <code>4 * 2</code> is constant, so <span class="hl">fold</span> it to <code>8</code> at compile time; <code>+ 0</code> simplifies away; a value computed twice is reused; unreachable branches are dropped as dead code. Step the passes and watch a small program collapse to a single constant.</p>
    <Optimize client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Optimization is a search for a cheaper program that computes the identical answer — the user never sees the difference, except in speed.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Most passes run on an <b>SSA</b>-form IR, where each variable is assigned exactly once. Single definitions make <b>constant propagation</b> and <b>dead-code elimination</b> almost trivial — a value's one definition is right there to fold or delete — and where control flow merges, a <code>φ</code> (phi) node picks the value from whichever predecessor block ran.</p>
      <p>Passes also <b>enable each other</b>, which is why compilers iterate to a fixpoint: <b>inlining</b> a function exposes its arguments as constants, which lets constant folding fire, which makes a branch unreachable, which lets dead-code elimination delete it. The flip side is the <b>phase-ordering problem</b> — there's no universally optimal sequence, so optimizers run carefully tuned, sometimes repeated, pass pipelines.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Straightforward code generation is correct but wasteful: redundant computation, values recomputed, branches that can never run."
      idea="Apply meaning-preserving rewrites — constant folding, dead-code elimination, inlining, common-subexpression elimination — guided by what the IR proves is safe."
      tradeoff="Optimizations must never change behavior, which makes them subtle; aggressive ones cost compile time and can expose latent bugs."
      next="Optimized or not, something finally has to execute the program."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.KR}>
    <p class="prose">Optimized bytecode still has to land on real hardware, where arithmetic runs only in a few fast <b>registers</b>. First the compiler rewrites into <span class="hl">SSA</span> — every assignment makes a new, single-definition value — so each value's <b>live range</b> is clear. Then it <b>allocates</b>: values alive at the same moment need different registers, and when more are live than the machine has, one is <span class="hl">spilled</span> to memory. Step it and watch four values fight over two registers.</p>
    <Registers client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Register allocation maps a program's unlimited values onto a fixed, tiny set of registers — and when they don't fit, spills the overflow to the stack. Scarcer registers mean more spills and slower code.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="cpu" note="the registers being fought over here — the CPU's fastest, scarcest storage" />
    <Advanced>
      <p>Classic allocation is posed as <b>graph colouring</b>: build an <b>interference graph</b> whose nodes are live ranges and whose edges join any two values live at the same time, then colour it with <i>k</i> colours (one per machine register) so no edge connects two same-coloured nodes. Chaitin's algorithm simplifies the graph by repeatedly removing low-degree nodes; if it gets stuck, it picks a victim to <b>spill</b> to a stack slot and tries again.</p>
      <p>Good allocators don't spill blindly — they weight each candidate by use frequency to avoid spilling a value used inside a hot loop. JITs that can't afford <i>k</i>-colouring instead use <b>linear-scan</b> allocation, which sweeps the sorted live ranges once; it's far faster to run and only a little worse, which is exactly the trade a just-in-time compiler wants.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A program names as many values as it likes, but the CPU has only a handful of registers, and memory is an order of magnitude slower to touch."
      idea="Compute each value's live range (easy once in SSA), then assign registers so values live at the same time never share one — spilling the rare overflow to a stack slot."
      tradeoff="Optimal allocation is NP-hard (graph colouring), so compilers use fast heuristics; every spill it can't avoid is extra load/store traffic at runtime."
      next="Allocated or spilled, the instructions are finally ready to execute — interpreted, compiled, or JIT-compiled."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K6}>
    <p class="prose">Three ways to actually run it: an <b>interpreter</b> walks the bytecode op by op (simple, portable, slower); an <b>ahead-of-time compiler</b> emits machine code once (fast start, less portable); a <b>JIT</b> interprets first, then compiles the <span class="hl">hot paths</span> to native code while running. Run the loop and watch which is cheapest flip as the iteration count climbs.</p>
    <Runtimes client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Interpret, compile ahead of time, or JIT — the same pipeline, differing only in when (and whether) bytecode becomes machine code.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="languages" note="which real languages (C, Rust, Go, Python, JS) pick each of these strategies" />
    <Advanced>
      <p>Production JITs (V8, the JVM's HotSpot) are <b>tiered</b>: code starts in a fast-to-emit baseline tier that also <b>profiles</b> — counting calls, recording which types actually flow through. When a method gets hot, an optimizing tier recompiles it using that profile, making <b>speculative</b> assumptions a static compiler can't, like "this dynamically-typed variable has always been an integer."</p>
      <p>Those bets need an escape hatch. The JIT plants <b>guards</b> that check the assumption; if one fails — a new type shows up — it <b>deoptimizes</b>, discarding the specialized code and falling back to the interpreter mid-execution, reconstructing the interpreter's stack frame on the spot. This is how managed languages reach near-native speed while staying correct when the program does something the profile never saw.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Producing operations isn't enough — they have to execute, and the right strategy depends on startup time, peak speed, and portability."
      idea="Pick where on the spectrum to sit: interpret bytecode directly, compile it all up front, or compile just the parts that run hot, just in time."
      tradeoff="Interpreters are slow but simple; AOT is fast but rigid; JITs are fast and adaptive but carry a compiler at runtime and warm-up cost."
      next="Zoom out: this whole pipeline is one rung of the climb from electrons to the cloud."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.K7}>
    <p class="prose">End to end: <b>source</b> text is <b>scanned</b> into tokens, <b>parsed</b> into a tree that fixes precedence, <b>type-checked</b> for meaning, <b>lowered</b> into linear bytecode, <b>optimized</b> to do less, <b>allocated</b> into the CPU's registers, and finally <b>run</b> — interpreted or compiled down to the numbered instructions the CPU obeys.</p>
    <Takeaway>"Running a program" is this entire pipeline — most of it usually finished before your code ever executes a line.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>The stages aren't always run by one program ahead of time. A <b>separate-compilation</b> model compiles each source file to an object file independently, then a <b>linker</b> stitches them together — resolving cross-file symbols and relocations — which is what makes incremental builds and shared libraries possible. The same pipeline can also run <i>during</i> execution (a JIT) or even at <b>build time as macros</b> that generate AST before the main passes.</p>
      <p>The deepest reason every stage can trust the next is a chain of <b>semantic preservation</b>: each lowering must keep the program's observable behaviour identical. When that's proven rather than merely tested, you get a <b>verified compiler</b> like <code>CompCert</code>, whose machine-checked proof guarantees the emitted assembly behaves exactly as the C source specifies.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="It's easy to think of code as something the computer just reads and does; the gap between text and execution is invisible until it breaks."
      idea="Each stage hands a cleaner, lower-level representation to the next — characters to tokens to tree to operations to machine code."
      tradeoff="The pipeline buys expressive languages and portability at the cost of build complexity, and leaky abstractions (compile errors, performance cliffs) when a stage's assumptions break."
      next="This is the bridge the main stack's Runtime layer points at — the rest of the climb is the machine that runs the result."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <Quiz slug="compiler" client:visible />
  <PrevNext slug="compiler" />
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link{color:var(--accent,var(--signal))}
</style>
